CP||FP||at|
^C@e@2With no intervening bid or double, responder is required to bid with 6 points or more. The reason @E@3for this is that opener can have up to 20 points or so, and if responder passes with 6 or more points, game might be missed. However, once there is an intervening takeout double (or overcall for that matter), opener has another chance to bid even if responder passes. Therefore, responder is relieved of the responsibility of having to bid, even with 6 or more points, and should only do so if he has something important to add to the auction.

Up to a few years ago, responder's choices over an intervening takeout double were easy. Responder|cp|8|aT| redoubled|CP||AT| with 10 or more points. Any suit bid showed a 5+ card suit, and less than 10 points. A |cp|8|at|1N |cp||at|response was "constructive", showing 8-10 points and inviting a raise from opener if he had more than a minimum hand.

This basic structure still holds, up to a point. |cp|8|at|Jordan 2N |cp||at|bids were added, showing a limit raise or better in opener's suit. The biggest change was that most experts now play that a one level bid by responder is now forcing, and. although it can be done on as little as six points, it can also be done with 10 or more points (in other words, it shows the same thing, more or less, as if there were no intervening takeout double). 

Two level bids are not forcing, and still show less than 10 points (responder can still redouble). Responder is not obligated to make a one level bid with a weak hand of up to 8 points. He should only do so with a good suit (if only 4 cards, then it should include a high honor or two.) Remember that the takeout doubler is ostensibly showing good support for all unbid suits, especially majors, so responder should avoid bidding a weak 4 card suit if he also has a weak hand. 

We can now resume the play of the hand.|
