^D @g@2"Up The Line"  refers to one very specific situation when pard opens one of a minor. If you have @E@34 hearts and 4 spades, you respond "up the line", meaning you bid hearts first. Several years ago, it also meant that if partner opened 1@C, and you had 4 diamonds and at least one 4 card major, you responded 1@D (again, bidding 4 card suits "up the line"). In modern bridge, many experts prefer what is known as "Walsh" when partner opens 1@C, bypassing even a long diamond suit to show a 4 card major. Similarly, as opener, if partner responds 1@D to your 1@C, "up the line" means that if you have both 4 hearts and 4 spades (e.g. your distribution is 4-4-2-3), you bid 1@H rather than 1@S. Therefore, "up the line" did not apply to the hand in question.

In general, as opener, your first obligation is to raise responder's suit if possible. Thus, on the hand in question, kia should raise 1@D to 2@D. Similarly, let us assume you are 4-4-2-3 and partner bids 1@H over your 1@C opener. You should bid 2@H rather than 1@S, even though you have 4 spades.

I have a few problems with  1N rebid over 1@D on the hand in question. First of all, as we already discussed, it denies diamond support. Also, the hand does not really have NT distribution, since it has 2 doubletons. And, finally, the stoppers in both of the unbid suits (Kx) are somewhat weak. Just because in this case we didn't get to 3N is not a justification for making an incorrect bid.  |
